00:29:43,824 --> 00:29:45,531
(ALARM BLARING)

253
00:29:49,871 --> 00:29:53,739
<i>The gamma's too high!
Bruce, I can't stop it!</i>

254
00:29:56,545 --> 00:29:58,502
Harper, get out!

255
00:29:59,047 --> 00:30:00,378
Get out!

256
00:30:09,224 --> 00:30:14,060
(HEART BEATING)

257
00:30:25,490 --> 00:30:26,730
(DOOR OPENING)

258
00:30:27,576 --> 00:30:30,409
How's Harper?
He's all right.

259
00:30:30,912 --> 00:30:32,448
You saved him.

260
00:30:33,081 --> 00:30:36,073
I don't think he's coming back
to the lab for a while, though.

261
00:30:42,090 --> 00:30:44,582
I don't understand
how this is possible.

262
00:30:46,219 --> 00:30:47,926
You should be dead.

263
00:30:50,223 --> 00:30:51,713
They worked,

264
00:30:52,434 --> 00:30:53,595
the nanomeds.

265
00:30:54,603 --> 00:30:56,389
I mean, I feel great.
I feel like...

266
00:30:56,855 --> 00:30:58,846
I don't know. They
must have, like, fixed me.

267
00:30:58,940 --> 00:31:02,683
Bruce, they've killed everything
else that they've come into contact with.

268
00:31:05,739 --> 00:31:07,150
Are you sure the doctor checked?

269
00:31:07,240 --> 00:31:08,822
The doctor gave me
the full workup.

270
00:31:08,909 --> 00:31:11,276
He wants to know where
he can get what I'm taking.

271
00:31:12,037 --> 00:31:13,573
I'm 100%.

272
00:31:14,873 --> 00:31:16,204
More.

273
00:31:17,250 --> 00:31:20,117
What do you mean?
Remember my bad knee?

274
00:31:21,171 --> 00:31:22,878
(LAUGHS)
Well, now it's my good knee.

275
00:31:24,174 --> 00:31:26,632
Bruce, this isn't funny.

276
00:31:27,511 --> 00:31:29,047
I was watching you.

277
00:31:29,388 --> 00:31:32,881
<i>You were gonna die, and I
was gonna have to watch you die.</i>

278
00:31:34,351 --> 00:31:37,764
Betty, I'm sorry.

279
00:31:40,273 --> 00:31:41,763
Really.

280
00:31:43,026 --> 00:31:45,643
Hey, I'm not gonna explode.
Okay?

281
00:31:46,446 --> 00:31:47,481
(CRYING) Yeah.

282
00:31:47,531 --> 00:31:48,566
(SNIFFLING)

283
00:31:48,657 --> 00:31:50,318
You should get some rest.

284
00:31:51,451 --> 00:31:52,862
And I'm fine, really.

285
00:31:55,205 --> 00:31:56,991
I've never felt better.

286
00:32:08,343 --> 00:32:10,334
(PANTING)

287
00:32:47,007 --> 00:32:48,714
(DOGS WHIMPERING)

288
00:32:59,978 --> 00:33:03,642
Your name is not Krenzler.
It's Banner.

289
00:33:08,361 --> 00:33:11,103
What?
Your name, it's Banner.

290
00:33:12,240 --> 00:33:13,776
Bruce Banner.

291
00:33:14,743 --> 00:33:16,074
Bruce.

292
00:33:18,580 --> 00:33:21,242
How did you get in here?
I work here now.

293
00:33:21,583 --> 00:33:23,870
In the labs. The late shift.

294
00:33:25,170 --> 00:33:27,127
It keeps me close to you.

295
00:33:28,131 --> 00:33:31,294
You always work so late
yourself with your friend Miss Ross.

296
00:33:32,719 --> 00:33:35,507
No, no. Please.
Please. Let me.

297
00:33:39,351 --> 00:33:40,933
You're not well.

298
00:33:42,229 --> 00:33:44,391
You've had a terrible accident.

299
00:33:46,650 --> 00:33:48,766
You're wondering
why you're still alive.

300
00:33:51,696 --> 00:33:54,654
You're thinking
there's something inside.

301
00:33:55,784 --> 00:33:57,900
Something different,

302
00:34:00,080 --> 00:34:01,536
inexplicable.

303
00:34:03,458 --> 00:34:07,668
I can help you understand,
if you'll let me.

304
00:34:10,131 --> 00:34:11,496
If you'll

305
00:34:13,426 --> 00:34:14,837
forgive me.

306
00:34:19,099 --> 00:34:23,639
Look, mister, I'm sure I have
nothing to forgive you for.

307
00:34:25,313 --> 00:34:28,977
So perhaps you should
leave now. I'll be fine.

308
00:34:29,276 --> 00:34:30,812
You must know.

309
00:34:31,903 --> 00:34:36,898
<i>You may not want to believe
it, but I can see it in your eyes.</i>

310
00:34:38,535 --> 00:34:40,742
<i>So much like your mother's.</i>

311
00:34:42,205 --> 00:34:44,492
Of course,
you're my flesh and blood.

312
00:34:45,166 --> 00:34:48,500
But then you're something
else, too, aren't you?

313
00:34:49,754 --> 00:34:51,495
My physical son,

314
00:34:52,507 --> 00:34:54,544
but the child of my mind, too.

315
00:34:56,219 --> 00:34:58,836
No. You're lying.

316
00:34:59,598 --> 00:35:01,509
My parents died
when I was a small boy.

317
00:35:01,558 --> 00:35:05,552
No, no, that's not true. That's
what they wanted you to believe.

318
00:35:05,895 --> 00:35:09,058
The experiments, the accident,
all top secret.

319
00:35:09,149 --> 00:35:13,518
They put me away
for 30 years. Thirty years!

320
00:35:15,697 --> 00:35:19,156
Away from you.
Away from our work.

321
00:35:21,077 --> 00:35:22,863
<i>But they couldn't
keep me forever.</i>

322
00:35:22,954 --> 00:35:25,286
After all, I'm sane.
They had to admit it.

323
00:35:27,626 --> 00:35:29,663
You see,

324
00:35:30,003 --> 00:35:33,871
everything
your extraordinary mind

325
00:35:34,549 --> 00:35:37,462
has been seeking
all these years,

326
00:35:38,136 --> 00:35:39,968
<i>it's been inside you.</i>

327
00:35:40,889 --> 00:35:43,130
Now we will understand it.

328
00:35:43,475 --> 00:35:45,307
We will harness it.

329
00:35:46,019 --> 00:35:47,384
(PHONE RINGING)

330
00:35:47,437 --> 00:35:50,225
No, don't answer it.
It's Miss Ross again.

331
00:35:50,315 --> 00:35:52,977
There's something you need
to know about her, Bruce.

332
00:35:53,109 --> 00:35:54,645
Something troublesome.

333
00:35:54,903 --> 00:35:56,644
Let me protect you from her.

334
00:35:57,781 --> 00:35:59,897
No. Get out.

335
00:36:00,700 --> 00:36:01,815
Bruce Get out!

336
00:36:01,910 --> 00:36:02,910
(SNARLING)

337
00:36:02,994 --> 00:36:04,075
Sit!

338
00:36:10,543 --> 00:36:12,125
(DOGS WHIMPERING)

339
00:36:21,888 --> 00:36:24,926
We're gonna have to watch
that temper of yours.

340
00:36:38,697 --> 00:36:40,358
(GAS HISSING)

341
00:36:50,291 --> 00:36:51,781
(DOGS WHIMPERING)

342
00:36:57,549 --> 00:36:59,131
(SNARLING)

343
00:37:05,140 --> 00:37:06,346
BETTY: You sure you're okay?

344
00:37:06,433 --> 00:37:08,470
BRUCE: Yeah,
just glad to be out of bed.

345
00:37:09,811 --> 00:37:14,305
Got a message from my father.
He's coming to see me.

346
00:37:15,150 --> 00:37:16,150
Your father?

347
00:37:16,526 --> 00:37:19,814
When?
Lands in about an hour.

348
00:37:21,114 --> 00:37:23,321
BETTY: The funny thing is,
he called me.

349
00:37:25,827 --> 00:37:27,488
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

350
00:37:35,044 --> 00:37:37,502
Hi, Dad.
Hello, Betty.

351
00:37:47,932 --> 00:37:49,343
WAITRESS: Here, ma'am.
Thanks.

352
00:37:49,434 --> 00:37:51,345
You're welcome. Sir?
Thank you.

353
00:37:51,436 --> 00:37:52,722
You're welcome.

354
00:38:02,030 --> 00:38:07,241
Look, I'm gonna get right to it.
It's about Glenn, isn't it?

355
00:38:08,620 --> 00:38:10,702
He's been snooping
around my lab.

356
00:38:11,122 --> 00:38:15,366
Glenn noticed some things,
asked me to make some inquiries.

357
00:38:18,838 --> 00:38:21,296
Are you here to question me?

358
00:38:21,841 --> 00:38:22,876
No.

359
00:38:23,885 --> 00:38:26,092
We've turned up
some surprising things.

360
00:38:29,182 --> 00:38:31,423
This Krenzler you work with,

361
00:38:32,143 --> 00:38:34,054
you know who he really is?

362
00:38:35,313 --> 00:38:37,475
How much do you actually
know about him?

363
00:38:38,650 --> 00:38:43,190
<i>I think the question is, what
is it that you know about him?</i>

364
00:38:46,282 --> 00:38:47,593
Well, right now,
I'm not at liberty...

365
00:38:47,617 --> 00:38:50,985
Not at liberty to disclose
it to me. Right. Right.

366
00:38:52,914 --> 00:38:55,997
<i>You know, I think I was hoping</i>

367
00:38:56,084 --> 00:39:02,080
that maybe this time you just
honestly wanted to see me again.

368
00:39:03,758 --> 00:39:06,250
You've got this all
wrong, Betty. Do I?

369
00:39:06,427 --> 00:39:10,045
<i>Yes. I do want to see you.</i>

370
00:39:12,892 --> 00:39:15,600
I really wish that
I could believe you.

371
00:40:03,860 --> 00:40:07,444
DAVID: Everything
your extraordinary mind

372
00:40:07,530 --> 00:40:10,397
<i>has been seeking
all these years,</i>

373
00:40:11,242 --> 00:40:13,199
it's been inside you.

374
00:40:18,666 --> 00:40:20,373
(PHONE RINGING)

375
00:40:33,222 --> 00:40:34,992
BRUCE ON ANSWERING
MACHINE: Hi, you've called Dr. Krenzler.

376
00:40:35,016 --> 00:40:37,348
Please leave a message
and I'll call you right back.

377
00:40:37,769 --> 00:40:39,259
(ANSWERING MACHINE BEEPS)

378
00:40:39,354 --> 00:40:41,937
BETTY: Bruce, hey.
Are you there?

379
00:40:43,566 --> 00:40:46,684
<i>Look, I think I screwed up.
My father...</i>

380
00:40:47,445 --> 00:40:50,187
<i>It's like he suspects you
of something. I don't know.</i>

381
00:40:51,032 --> 00:40:53,524
I was so impatient, like always.

382
00:40:53,576 --> 00:40:55,692
<i>I didn't hear him out.
I don't know, I...</i>

383
00:40:56,412 --> 00:40:59,746
that they're planning
something with the lab.

384
00:40:59,832 --> 00:41:01,998
So, (GRUNTS)

385
00:41:02,085 --> 00:41:04,167
call me. Okay? Bye.

386
00:41:07,298 --> 00:41:08,298
Betty?

387
00:41:13,262 --> 00:41:14,752
(GROWLING)

388
00:41:19,268 --> 00:41:20,554
(DOG WHIMPERING)

389
00:41:35,910 --> 00:41:37,241
(GROANING)

390
00:41:39,747 --> 00:41:41,112
(BRUCE ROARING)

391
00:41:44,085 --> 00:41:45,667
(SCREAMING)

392
00:42:07,025 --> 00:42:09,107
(YELLING)

393
00:42:17,952 --> 00:42:19,283
(YELLING)

394
00:42:44,020 --> 00:42:45,306
(GROWLING)

395
00:42:45,897 --> 00:42:48,639
Dispatch! Dispatch!
We have a 415 at the lab!

396
00:42:48,733 --> 00:42:51,145
Send the Berkeley P.D. now!
Send them now!

397
00:42:58,326 --> 00:42:59,566
(GROWLING)

398
00:43:01,454 --> 00:43:02,944
(SIREN WAILING)

399
00:43:07,418 --> 00:43:08,704
(ROARING)

400
00:43:18,513 --> 00:43:20,345
Watch out!

401
00:44:26,080 --> 00:44:28,663
DAVID: Edith?
EDITH: David, what's going on?

402
00:44:29,917 --> 00:44:32,579
<i>I gotta talk to you, Edith.
Bruce, stay here.</i>

403
00:44:32,962 --> 00:44:34,498
(GROWLING)

404
00:44:38,134 --> 00:44:39,249
<i>(GASPING)</i>

405
00:44:46,893 --> 00:44:48,600
(ROARING)

406
00:45:03,242 --> 00:45:05,028
(POLICE SIREN WAILING)

407
00:45:05,119 --> 00:45:07,235
My Bruce.

408
00:45:13,002 --> 00:45:14,333
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

409
00:45:21,636 --> 00:45:23,172
Bruce?

410
00:46:00,007 --> 00:46:01,668
<i>There was some
sort of explosion.</i>

411
00:46:01,759 --> 00:46:04,091
They wouldn't let us
into the building.

412
00:46:06,264 --> 00:46:08,096
I was worried about you.

413
00:46:09,016 --> 00:46:11,348
Well, I'm okay.

414
00:46:13,312 --> 00:46:15,223
What happened to you last night?

415
00:46:16,899 --> 00:46:18,936
I had the most vivid dream.

416
00:46:21,445 --> 00:46:23,061
It was like being born.

417
00:46:23,614 --> 00:46:27,733
Coming up for air. Light
hitting my face. Screaming.

418
00:46:29,412 --> 00:46:30,743
My heartbeat,

419
00:46:32,164 --> 00:46:34,405
it was like boom,

420
00:46:35,543 --> 00:46:37,079
boom,

421
00:46:39,297 --> 00:46:40,753
boom.

422
00:46:46,762 --> 00:46:50,096
Were you at the lab?
No.

423
00:46:51,642 --> 00:46:53,224
But something...

424
00:46:56,147 --> 00:47:00,015
<i>And there was that man,
the one with the dogs.</i>

425
00:47:00,651 --> 00:47:02,233
Who?

426
00:47:03,612 --> 00:47:05,228
That new janitor.

427
00:47:06,407 --> 00:47:07,989
He said he was my father.

428
00:47:10,619 --> 00:47:11,950
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

429
00:47:14,498 --> 00:47:15,738
I'll get it.

430
00:47:26,510 --> 00:47:27,545
(INAUDIBLE) My father.

431
00:47:37,188 --> 00:47:38,678
My, my.

432
00:47:40,191 --> 00:47:42,398
<i>So this is the young
Bruce Ban...</i>

433
00:47:44,820 --> 00:47:46,185
Krenzler.

434
00:47:48,324 --> 00:47:51,112
I think you left something
in your lab last night.

435
00:47:55,414 --> 00:47:59,783
Mitchell, escort my daughter
outside. I'll join her shortly.

436
00:48:01,045 --> 00:48:03,628
I'd rather stay here.
Now, Betty.

437
00:48:06,926 --> 00:48:10,339
It's okay. I'll be fine.

438
00:48:21,482 --> 00:48:23,689
Keep him under observation.
I'll be back.

439
00:48:31,742 --> 00:48:34,029
What?
Your friend in there,

440
00:48:34,620 --> 00:48:38,284
there's a good chance he's caught
up in some very bad business,

441
00:48:38,332 --> 00:48:40,164
unfinished business.

442
00:48:40,668 --> 00:48:43,330
And I promise you, I'm
gonna get to the bottom of it.

443
00:48:43,963 --> 00:48:46,546
You have my word
I'll make sure he's cared for.

444
00:48:46,632 --> 00:48:49,420
But as of right now,
he is incommunicado.

445
00:48:49,635 --> 00:48:51,842
And for the next
few days at least,

446
00:48:51,929 --> 00:48:53,715
you're gonna stay away
from here.

447
00:48:54,014 --> 00:48:55,721
For your own good.

448
00:49:04,275 --> 00:49:07,063
Okay, and that's for the new
guy on the night shift, right?

449
00:49:07,987 --> 00:49:10,024
Great. Thank you.
I appreciate it.

450
00:49:23,502 --> 00:49:24,867
(DOGS BARKING)

451
00:49:28,799 --> 00:49:30,381
Dr. Ross.

452
00:49:31,719 --> 00:49:33,175
How unexpected.

453
00:49:34,138 --> 00:49:36,004
Please come in.

454
00:49:40,728 --> 00:49:44,437
I'm sorry to just show up
at your house like this.

455
00:49:49,487 --> 00:49:51,353
I came to ask you something

456
00:49:51,405 --> 00:49:54,989
<i>that I really have
no business asking.</i>

457
00:49:57,620 --> 00:49:59,076
He told you?

458
00:50:00,080 --> 00:50:02,492
He said you talked to him.
Oh.

459
00:50:03,918 --> 00:50:05,329
Please sit down.

460
00:50:14,386 --> 00:50:16,252
Bruce was at the lab last night.

461
00:50:16,305 --> 00:50:18,171
He said that
you were there, too.

462
00:50:18,349 --> 00:50:20,306
<i>But he can't remember
much about it.</i>

463
00:50:21,268 --> 00:50:23,134
I need to find out
what happened.

464
00:50:23,854 --> 00:50:27,267
So, you want to know
what's wrong with him,

465
00:50:28,442 --> 00:50:30,058
so you can fix him?

466
00:50:30,903 --> 00:50:33,065
Cure him, change him.

467
00:50:34,949 --> 00:50:36,940
My father's with the military.

468
00:50:37,451 --> 00:50:41,319
He seems to think he's involved in
some kind of threat to national security.

469
00:50:41,413 --> 00:50:42,574
(GROANING)

470
00:50:42,790 --> 00:50:45,452
Your father. Ross.

471
00:50:47,127 --> 00:50:50,916
You brought your father
down upon his head?

472
00:50:51,340 --> 00:50:53,832
How little you understand,
Miss Ross,

473
00:50:53,968 --> 00:50:57,302
and how dangerous
your ignorance has become.

474
00:50:59,557 --> 00:51:01,798
I'm sorry.
Don't be sorry.

475
00:51:02,560 --> 00:51:06,474
My son is unique.

476
00:51:07,314 --> 00:51:09,271
<i>That's why you can't
relate to him.</i>

477
00:51:10,150 --> 00:51:14,610
And because he is unique, the
world will not tolerate his existence.

478
00:51:14,655 --> 00:51:15,986
Will they?

479
00:51:17,074 --> 00:51:18,690
But you,

480
00:51:20,869 --> 00:51:23,861
you try, don't you?

481
00:51:25,833 --> 00:51:27,073
Yes.

482
00:51:31,839 --> 00:51:35,127
And a very beautiful
woman like you,

483
00:51:36,010 --> 00:51:37,626
your attentions

484
00:51:38,345 --> 00:51:41,758
can't be completely unwanted.

485
00:51:42,683 --> 00:51:44,173
Can they?

486
00:51:45,728 --> 00:51:46,843
No.

487
00:51:48,105 --> 00:51:51,018
Not with eyes like yours,

488
00:51:52,192 --> 00:51:56,652
watching expectantly, lovingly.

489
00:52:00,200 --> 00:52:02,988
But I'm afraid we're both
too late to help him.

490
00:52:03,203 --> 00:52:07,538
There's nothing I can do
for him or for you.

491
00:52:08,542 --> 00:52:09,828
Besides,

492
00:52:10,836 --> 00:52:13,544
he's made it clear he wants
nothing to do with me.

493
00:52:13,756 --> 00:52:15,417
His choice.

494
00:52:15,507 --> 00:52:19,421
Now if you'll excuse me,
Miss Ross, I got
some work to do.

495
00:52:20,220 --> 00:52:22,757
And don't worry about the dogs.

496
00:52:22,973 --> 00:52:26,716
You'll be fine. Just don't
look them in the eyes.

497
00:52:30,147 --> 00:52:31,182
Goodbye.

498
00:52:34,068 --> 00:52:37,026
ROSS: He gets released, and a
month later your lab is destroyed.

499
00:52:37,071 --> 00:52:38,561
What a coincidence.

500
00:52:38,822 --> 00:52:41,564
So you're just not gonna
tell me where he is, are you?

501
00:52:41,700 --> 00:52:43,532
<i>How many times
do I have to tell you?</i>

502
00:52:43,577 --> 00:52:45,318
I'd like to help you,
but I just don't know.

503
00:52:45,412 --> 00:52:47,449
<i>You know who I am.
Right, Banner?</i>

504
00:52:47,748 --> 00:52:49,726
You're Betty's father.
You're a high-ranking general.

505
00:52:49,750 --> 00:52:51,081
Let's cut the crap.

506
00:52:51,168 --> 00:52:53,500
I'm the guy who had
your father tossed away,

507
00:52:53,587 --> 00:52:54,587
and a lot more like him,

508
00:52:54,630 --> 00:52:57,042
and I'll do the same with you
if I feel so disposed.

509
00:52:57,091 --> 00:52:58,297
You understand?

510
00:52:58,384 --> 00:53:00,876
If you had him tossed away,
then why are you asking me?

511
00:53:00,928 --> 00:53:02,794
<i>I don't remember.</i>

512
00:53:02,888 --> 00:53:04,720
I was always told
my father was dead.

513
00:53:04,765 --> 00:53:06,347
Don't play with me!

514
00:53:06,725 --> 00:53:09,092
You were four years old
when you saw it.

515
00:53:10,562 --> 00:53:11,768
<i>When I saw what?</i>

516
00:53:11,814 --> 00:53:15,432
You were right there. How could
anyone forget a thing like that?

517
00:53:17,903 --> 00:53:19,189
What?

518
00:53:19,863 --> 00:53:22,230
Oh, some more
repressed memories.

519
00:53:25,786 --> 00:53:27,197
Just tell me.

520
00:53:30,374 --> 00:53:31,785
I'm sorry, son.

521
00:53:33,544 --> 00:53:36,411
You're an even more screwed-up
mess than I thought you'd be.

522
00:53:38,298 --> 00:53:40,380
Until we get to
the bottom of this,

523
00:53:40,592 --> 00:53:43,425
your lab has been declared
a top-secret military site,

524
00:53:43,470 --> 00:53:46,508
and you're not gonna get a
security clearance to get back into it

525
00:53:46,807 --> 00:53:49,925
or any other lab that's doing
anything more interesting

526
00:53:50,352 --> 00:53:53,686
than trying to figure out the
next generation of herbal hair gel.

527
00:53:57,109 --> 00:53:58,599
One more thing.

528
00:53:59,820 --> 00:54:03,484
If you ever come
within 1,000 yards

529
00:54:03,574 --> 00:54:05,736
of my daughter again,

530
00:54:05,909 --> 00:54:09,152
I'll put you away for
the rest of your natural life.

531
00:54:13,250 --> 00:54:14,331
(SNIFFS)

532
00:54:23,677 --> 00:54:25,133
Dogs!

533
00:54:25,179 --> 00:54:26,761
(DOGS SNARLING)

534
00:54:27,639 --> 00:54:30,631
Go! Go get her!

535
00:54:30,976 --> 00:54:33,559
And let nothing stand
in your way!

536
00:54:35,022 --> 00:54:36,022
Go!

537
00:55:20,484 --> 00:55:21,849
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

538
00:55:40,754 --> 00:55:42,836
Hello?
DAVID: Bruce?

539
00:55:43,924 --> 00:55:47,963
So, they think they can just
throw you away as they did me.

540
00:55:56,520 --> 00:55:59,262
What's wrong with me?
What did you do to me?

541
00:55:59,439 --> 00:56:00,929
<i>I got a visit today.</i>

542
00:56:01,024 --> 00:56:03,391
A very unwelcome visit.

543
00:56:03,944 --> 00:56:06,276
I'm afraid my hand
is being forced.

544
00:56:06,947 --> 00:56:09,439
What did you do to me?

545
00:56:10,158 --> 00:56:12,570
You so much want to know,
don't you?

546
00:56:13,161 --> 00:56:16,779
<i>But I think no explanation
will serve you half as well</i>

547
00:56:17,040 --> 00:56:18,701
<i>as the experience.</i>

548
00:56:20,127 --> 00:56:23,665
In any case, I still don't
quite understand it myself.

549
00:56:24,464 --> 00:56:26,956
If they'd only let me
work in peace...

550
00:56:27,217 --> 00:56:30,300
Of course, my betters
would have none of that.

551
00:56:30,762 --> 00:56:33,470
BRUCE: So you experimented
on yourself, didn't you?

552
00:56:33,724 --> 00:56:36,307
And passed on to me, what?

553
00:56:37,352 --> 00:56:39,719
<i>An alteration. Genetic.</i>

554
00:56:40,272 --> 00:56:43,310
<i>A deformity. I guess
you could call it that.</i>

555
00:56:44,109 --> 00:56:46,396
But an amazing strength, too.

556
00:56:47,070 --> 00:56:50,608
And now, finally unleashed,
I can harvest it.

557
00:56:51,241 --> 00:56:52,241
BRUCE: No.

558
00:56:52,326 --> 00:56:55,990
You'll do no such thing. I will
isolate it and treat it myself.

559
00:56:56,330 --> 00:56:59,322
I'll remove it, and I'll kill it
before it does any real harm.

560
00:56:59,666 --> 00:57:02,658
I'll bet you and your Betty
would love to destroy it.

561
00:57:03,170 --> 00:57:06,379
But would you really destroy
part of yourself?

562
00:57:07,132 --> 00:57:08,714
<i>I don't think so.</i>

563
00:57:09,843 --> 00:57:11,174
And as for Betty,

564
00:57:11,803 --> 00:57:16,092
I'm sending her a surprise visit
from some four-legged friends of mine.

565
00:57:16,558 --> 00:57:20,677
You see, I've managed to culture
some of your very own DNA, Bruce,

566
00:57:21,021 --> 00:57:22,978
and the results are tremendous.

567
00:57:23,774 --> 00:57:26,857
They're unstable,
but very powerful.

568
00:57:28,946 --> 00:57:30,528
What about my DNA?

569
00:57:31,740 --> 00:57:35,404
Let's just wait and see what
Betty makes of the results, huh?

570
00:57:35,494 --> 00:57:39,032
No. You're crazy.
I won't let you.

571
00:57:40,374 --> 00:57:41,785
(CHATTERING)

572
00:57:42,709 --> 00:57:43,870
Get your hands off of me.

573
00:57:44,878 --> 00:57:47,370
Talbot, what's this...
Inside, asshole. I wanna talk to you.

574
00:57:47,631 --> 00:57:49,747
Listen to me, my father's
going after Betty...

575
00:57:49,841 --> 00:57:51,569
What makes you think
you can go behind my back

576
00:57:51,593 --> 00:57:53,209
and get Ross to cut me out, huh?

577
00:57:53,261 --> 00:57:54,501
(GROANS)

578
00:57:54,554 --> 00:57:56,636
Listen to me!
Betty's in trouble!

579
00:57:56,890 --> 00:57:58,881
(BOTH GRUNTING)

580
00:57:59,559 --> 00:58:01,049
You pathetic freak.

581
00:58:01,103 --> 00:58:03,470
Betty's in danger. I swear
to you, she'll be Killed.

582
00:58:03,563 --> 00:58:05,395
I can state the obvious.

583
00:58:05,691 --> 00:58:07,728
Something tells me you
aren't in much of a position

584
00:58:07,776 --> 00:58:10,234
to be making
stupid threats to anyone.

585
00:58:11,363 --> 00:58:12,728
(GRUNTING)

586
00:58:14,408 --> 00:58:16,399
<i>Talbot.
Yeah?</i>

587
00:58:16,576 --> 00:58:18,237
You're making me angry.

588
00:58:18,787 --> 00:58:20,073
Oh, am I?

589
00:58:31,008 --> 00:58:32,089
(GRUNTS)

